@Carlos 

Good afternoon Carlos,

   First, I wanted to say how well you looked at the graph and payed attention to details. I also had that same question but after reading some comments, I came to a realization. I want to help you answer your question “Why is there more social workers and healthcare workers?” I honestly believe that more people take these jobs because of the pay. Social work and healthcare work does pay more than other jobs like transportation and resource extraction. The biggest motivation for working is pay. If you are not going to make a lot of money, you may not want to work that job. I think that these women thought of that and decided to major in something different and make as much money as possible.

@Scout In response to your second point: Farmers are low on the graph not because there a few farmers but because there are few female farmers. You'll notice that the jobs aren't listed, top to bottom, in order of number of workers--they're listed in order of percentage female workers. This is why you have social workers--78% women but only 2,320,000 total workers--above health care workers--77% women and 19,090,000 total workers. If they were listed by total workers, health care would be at the top, but since there's a greater percentage of female social workers than female health care workers, social workers are at the top.

This is why farmers are so low on the list--not because there aren't many farmers, but because there aren't many women in farming. If you look at the total number of workers, farmers would actually rank a little above the middle of the graph. 

And keep in mind that while farmers are definitely some of the most essential workers we have, that doesn't mean you need that many of them. A single farm can produce food for thousands at once, whereas a single doctor can only save one person at once. The number of workers in a particular job isn't necessarily linked to how essential their work is.
